e real world of Christian and Jewish communities under Islamic rule. Finally, he considers what a more informed picture of the relationship among the Abrahamic faiths in the medieval Islamic world might mean for modern scholarship on medieval Islamic civilization and, not the least, for the highly contentious global environment of today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslam. 0aCivilization, Medieval. 0aEast and West. 0aIslamxRelationsxChristianity. 0aIslamxRelationsxJudaism. 0aIslamic learning and scholarshipxHistory. 0aJewszIslamic Empire. 0aJudaismxRelationsxIslam. 0aOrientalismxHistory. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  areligious studies, religion, faith, belief, scholarly, academic, research, medieval, middle ages, judaism, christianity, muslim, islam, christian, jewish, relationship, culture, cultural, political, politics, abrahamic, holy books, land, 13th century, primary source, rhetoric, literary, legal, laws, communities, tolerance, civilization, globalization, history, historical, muhammed, philosophy, polemics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022647107540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226471099423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226471099/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles